21:44.904 --> 21:48.105
-All right.
-[hissing]

21:50.443 --> 21:52.910
-[rogers chuckles]
-[amanda] let's see
what we've made here.

21:52.912 --> 21:56.981
Once we take the alcohol
out of the chamber,
we strain the pears

21:56.983 --> 21:57.948
<i>  to get all the liquor out.</i>

21:57.950 --> 21:59.684
-Smells like pears.
-[rogers] mmm-hmm

21:59.686 --> 22:01.085
<i> we've made it a little cloudy,</i>

22:01.087 --> 22:03.621
so instead of trying
to run this back
through a filtration system,

22:03.623 --> 22:05.823
<i>  we're gonna use the still</i>
<i>  as our filter this time.</i>

22:05.825 --> 22:09.260
<i>  And we'll redistill it,</i>
<i>  clean it up,</i>
<i>  and we're gonna get</i>

22:09.262 --> 22:10.928
a cleaner, smoother product
in the end.

22:10.930 --> 22:13.397
-[huck] eat ya one of them.
-[amanda] yeah, taste that.

22:17.470 --> 22:19.437
-Whoop.
-[rogers laughs]

22:23.042 --> 22:25.710
tastes a little bit
hot though, eh?

22:25.712 --> 22:27.478
<i>  That infusion really worked.</i>

22:27.480 --> 22:30.081
<i>  It's just about biting</i>
<i> into one of those large pears.</i>

22:30.083 --> 22:32.783
You know, that's how good
a flavor it is.

22:32.785 --> 22:33.851
It's like a pear corn brandy.

22:33.853 --> 22:35.720
<i> [rogers] but we need to try</i>
<i>  to clear it up.</i>

22:35.722 --> 22:38.856
If we can keep
this same flavor,
we'll really have something.

22:38.858 --> 22:42.993
We probably got, what?
Four or five more gallons
of this to infuse now?

22:42.995 --> 22:46.931
After infusing this corn
with the pears,
it tastes awesome.

22:46.933 --> 22:48.599
-[huck] here we go.
-[hissing]

22:48.601 --> 22:50.735
you tell me when to stop.

22:50.737 --> 22:53.904
I feel like we could take this
and sell this to anybody
and they would love it,

22:53.906 --> 22:55.206
<i>  but because we have</i>
<i>  the time now,</i>

22:55.208 --> 22:57.641
we can take this back
to the still and redistill it
and bring

22:57.643 --> 23:00.144
this pear corn whiskey
to a whole other level.

23:00.146 --> 23:02.213
Well, I guess it's back
to still side, isn't it?

23:02.882 --> 23:04.115
-Yeah.
-Think so.

23:04.117 --> 23:06.684
Load her up. Head that way.

23:06.719 --> 23:08.185
[rogers grunts]

23:18.998 --> 23:22.466
well, I tell you what, man.
You're gonna love
this damn place, brother.

23:22.468 --> 23:24.301
-I hope so.
-It's awesome.

23:24.303 --> 23:27.071
<i>  We're back in tennessee now</i>
<i>  to show jerry</i>
<i>  our new still site.</i>

23:27.073 --> 23:29.607
<i>  But just getting the stuff</i>
<i>  back across the mountain</i>
<i>  is one thing.</i>

23:29.609 --> 23:32.843
<i>  But getting it all the way up</i>
<i>  into the woods to where</i>
<i>  I found the still site.</i>

23:32.845 --> 23:35.613
We're just gonna have
to haul it in there
a couple pieces at a time

23:35.615 --> 23:37.815
<i>  until we get it all in there</i>
<i>  and set up.</i>

23:37.817 --> 23:40.084
I'll tell you what.
This is a pretty little trail
up through here.

23:40.086 --> 23:41.352
Yeah, it is.

23:43.723 --> 23:45.055
Park it right here.

23:45.124 --> 23:47.091
What do you think, bro?

23:48.161 --> 23:49.960
[jerry] son, I'm digging this.

23:49.996 --> 23:52.029
With a big, old, fat shovel.

23:52.565 --> 23:54.432
Why don't you look
at that water, brother.

23:54.434 --> 23:56.600
[mike] reckon we've got plenty
of it, did I not tell you?

23:56.602 --> 23:59.370
-[jerry] I don't think
it'll ever dry up on us.
-[mike] no, sir.

24:01.507 --> 24:02.873
-Is that not good?
-I was about to say
well that's

24:02.875 --> 24:06.444
some damn good water
right there
and cold, god!

24:06.446 --> 24:08.512
You can tell this place
has never been logged
or anything.

24:08.514 --> 24:12.149
The trees are just gigantic.
This waterfall's enormous.

24:12.151 --> 24:14.985
<i>  I think mike got us</i>
<i>  a really good site</i>
<i>  for the rest of the season.</i>

24:14.987 --> 24:17.621
Luckily, this right here
is about the only flat spot
we got.

24:17.623 --> 24:18.956
Right in this little area,
right here.

24:18.958 --> 24:21.826
[mike] with the setup we got,
it don't take much.

24:21.828 --> 24:24.161
[jerry] no, this little setup
we ain't got much at all.

24:24.163 --> 24:26.063
Run it here. Barrel to barrel.

24:26.065 --> 24:28.866
Set our mash barrels
right up against
that log right there.

24:28.868 --> 24:30.000
Keep it all nice and tight.

24:30.002 --> 24:32.269
That's right.
We'd kill
all this little stuff.

24:32.271 --> 24:34.872
That'd kind of open it up
right in here a little.

24:34.874 --> 24:37.975
I'm excited being back here
in east tennessee.

24:37.977 --> 24:39.577
<i>  Me and jerry, we've had</i>
<i>  our ups and downs.</i>

24:39.579 --> 24:42.780
But all our stuff's here
that we can work with.

24:42.782 --> 24:44.915
And I'm ready to hit
the ground running,
get me set up.

24:44.917 --> 24:46.917
Mike, I got this part.

24:46.919 --> 24:49.019
-I feel like I done
my part today.
-Yeah, you did.

24:49.021 --> 24:50.788
It's all right.

24:50.790 --> 24:53.424
You know, I got pretty strict
doctor's orders. I'm not gonna
overdo myself.

24:53.426 --> 24:56.861
My life is more valuable
than any still sites.

24:56.863 --> 24:58.662
We're in here now,
we'll get this little place
cleaned out.

24:58.664 --> 25:01.298
We'll get set up.
Gotta pop in water.

25:01.300 --> 25:03.801
It's only one damn step
at a time.
We can only do so much.

25:03.803 --> 25:05.836
My work for the day's done.

25:05.838 --> 25:07.905
I'm getting out
of this damn hollow
for a little while.

25:07.907 --> 25:09.206
-That'll work.
-Let's do it.

25:09.742 --> 25:11.642
<i> [mike] so, you owe me</i>
<i>  a steak dinner now,</i>
<i>  right, jerry?</i>

25:11.644 --> 25:14.111
<i> -[jerry] you got it.</i>
<i> -[mike laughs]</i>

25:16.015 --> 25:17.815
-[crackling leaves]
-[footsteps approaching]

25:17.817 --> 25:18.949
[gurgling water]

25:22.788 --> 25:24.255
<i> [digger] I know one thing.</i>

25:24.690 --> 25:27.791
It don't take long
to eat up them 40 or 50
dollars' worth of cherries.

25:27.793 --> 25:30.895
[richard] oh, no, I think
I ate about 30 yesterday.

25:30.897 --> 25:34.565
[digger] welcome
to our old still site,
richard.

25:34.567 --> 25:36.734
-Tried and true. We love it.
-[richard] man.

25:36.736 --> 25:38.602
Looks like home.
I'd have a hammock
up here

25:38.604 --> 25:40.871
and a little tent set up.
I wouldn't go nowhere.

25:40.873 --> 25:42.907
Well, you don't know
that the moonshiners
don't ever sit down.

25:42.909 --> 25:44.675
They sleep standing up.

25:44.677 --> 25:46.944
Normally, you don't walk
a stranger
into your still site.

25:46.946 --> 25:50.047
<i>  They're breaking</i>
<i>  rule number one for me.</i>

25:50.049 --> 25:51.715
<i> -[digger] that's big sloppy.</i>
<i> -[ramsey] and the baby.</i>

25:51.717 --> 25:53.951
<i> [digger] we're getting ready</i>
<i>  to mash all this in.</i>

25:53.953 --> 25:56.053
The sugar cane doesn't need
nothing else except adding
the mash,

25:56.055 --> 25:58.622
<i>  but these cherries are</i>
<i>  a little different story.</i>

25:58.624 --> 26:00.558
We gotta cook them up
or they'll cook apart.

26:00.560 --> 26:04.728
The seeds will come out
and we can eliminate those
from the process.

26:04.730 --> 26:08.566
[ramsey] I guess first thing
we need to do is get
that little still took apart.

26:08.568 --> 26:09.833
We just need the burner,
don't we?

26:09.835 --> 26:12.436
Gotta get us
a little water established.

26:14.907 --> 26:16.707
We got fresh cherries,
cane juice...

26:16.709 --> 26:21.045
[ramsey] we're making us
some hillbilly cajun cognac.

26:21.047 --> 26:23.213
This is definitely better
than what comes out
of the bayou.

26:23.215 --> 26:24.014
I can drink this right now.

26:24.016 --> 26:25.482
[digger] I'm gonna get
some cherries

26:25.484 --> 26:27.351
because I don't know
how much water we need.

26:27.353 --> 26:30.888
It really, really
is a hard job getting the pits
out of cherries.

26:30.890 --> 26:32.923
<i>  We've got a lot of cherries,</i>
<i>  so we're going to have to try</i>
<i>  to find a way</i>

26:32.925 --> 26:35.225
to get these pits
out of here effectively.

26:35.227 --> 26:37.962
We're definitely taking
those stems off of them.

26:37.964 --> 26:40.598
Cherries do so good
with liquor, man, but the work
you've gotta put into it.

26:40.600 --> 26:42.166
Exactly.

26:42.168 --> 26:45.803
-Damn watched pot
don't ever start a boil.
-That's what they told me.

26:45.805 --> 26:46.971
One of them's right here.

26:46.973 --> 26:49.607
[laughs] you might.
I can feel her getting softer.

26:49.609 --> 26:51.875
When you're dealing
with fruits,
it's very important

26:51.877 --> 26:55.980
to make sure you start
to break down the structure
so it can ferment effectively.

26:55.982 --> 26:58.482
-[digger] yeah,
they're getting mushy.
-Dropping the pits in there.

26:58.484 --> 27:00.084
Look, there's
a pit right there.

27:00.086 --> 27:02.086
You know, these cherries
are wonderful.

27:02.088 --> 27:04.922
They're not tart,
they're really sweet,
they're full of juice.

27:04.924 --> 27:06.991
<i>  It makes a beautiful mash.</i>

27:06.993 --> 27:10.461
We're gonna make us
a screen to pour
this damn gravy through.

27:10.463 --> 27:12.363
[digger] we're gonna
screen test it.

27:12.365 --> 27:14.732
That's what that policeman
did to me down there
in nashville that time.

27:14.734 --> 27:17.768
He slammed them brakes
on there, was handcuffing,
then bam!

27:17.770 --> 27:20.804
-I said,
"boy, that was a screen test."
-[richard laughs]

27:20.806 --> 27:22.906
<i> [digger] the screen</i>
<i>  we're gonna build,</i>
<i>  it's simple.</i>

27:22.908 --> 27:25.342
<i>  It's just a square</i>
<i>  made out of two by fours.</i>

27:27.947 --> 27:30.080
<i>  We'll just pack</i>
<i>  some chicken wire</i>

27:30.082 --> 27:32.850
kind of like what you build
to build a fish trap
or a minnow trap.

27:32.852 --> 27:33.817
[ramsey] look at that.

27:33.819 --> 27:35.052
Hell, that looks like
that'll work.

27:35.054 --> 27:37.287
Now we just gotta get it
out of this pot.

27:38.858 --> 27:41.025
<i> [digger] when it comes</i>
<i>  to the stones is,</i>

27:41.027 --> 27:42.860
they used to call
the seed and the fruit,

27:42.862 --> 27:45.663
<i>  not only can</i>
<i>  they produce wood alcohol,</i>
<i>  which is a no-no,</i>

27:45.665 --> 27:48.866
<i>  seeds also can</i>
<i>  contain cyanide.</i>

27:48.868 --> 27:52.903
We eliminate that altogether,
just where that doesn't
have to be a concern.

27:52.905 --> 27:54.705
I know this is the pits,
doing this stuff.

27:54.707 --> 27:57.408
-You're a clever man,
richard landry.
-[chuckles]

27:57.410 --> 27:59.543
<i> [richard] so, the pits</i>
<i>  will stay at the top</i>
<i>  of this screen</i>

27:59.545 --> 28:03.714
and we'll have all our flesh
and our cherry juice
in the bucket.

28:03.716 --> 28:06.684
[digger] I'm gonna nut-bust,
and any of you can scrape,
how's that?

28:06.686 --> 28:08.552
[richard] they're still hot
<i>  in there.</i>

28:08.554 --> 28:09.920
<i>  We have these cherries</i>
<i>  heated up.</i>

28:09.922 --> 28:11.655
<i>  We brought 'em</i>
<i>  to a temperature would help</i>

28:11.657 --> 28:12.723
break down a little bit more

28:12.725 --> 28:13.991
what we need broken down
from this.

28:13.993 --> 28:15.592
<i>  Start doing</i>
<i>  a real good ferment.</i>

28:15.594 --> 28:17.127
<i>  We're gonna throw</i>
<i>  our sugar cane in there,</i>

28:17.129 --> 28:19.463
let it cool down,
and we'll pitch some yeast.

28:19.465 --> 28:21.999
That's sugar cane juice,
right there.

28:22.001 --> 28:27.071
If each of these buckets
was equivalent
to 50 pounds of sugar,

28:27.106 --> 28:28.672
<i>  then we've got plenty.</i>

28:28.674 --> 28:30.174
The more sugar,
the more alcohol.

28:30.176 --> 28:31.709
Boys, we're running out
of daylight.

28:31.711 --> 28:32.776
-We gotta pitch this yeast.
-Pitch it.

28:32.778 --> 28:35.045
-This temperature's
good, I mean...
-Mmm-hmm.

28:35.047 --> 28:38.215
We don't need a bunch of it.
Just about a good cupful
in there.

28:38.217 --> 28:39.116
Scattered on top.

28:39.118 --> 28:40.884
All we got to do
is top that off.

28:40.886 --> 28:42.686
Let it do its magic.

28:42.688 --> 28:44.755
We're gonna let you
cap that rascal off,
there, richard.

28:44.757 --> 28:46.990
Oh, man. Y'all gonna let me
cap off this pot?

28:46.992 --> 28:49.893
Line it up with that.
I'm gonna put it
in this thump arm.

28:49.895 --> 28:52.563
That way, we don't get
no unwanted critters.

28:52.565 --> 28:54.765
There's a lot of people think
that they're moonshiners,

28:54.767 --> 28:56.934
and they ain't got a still
as big as that cap.

28:56.936 --> 28:59.636
[digger] till you unload
two truckloads
of sugar a week,

28:59.638 --> 29:01.939
you ain't no moonshiner.

29:08.647 --> 29:11.048
<i> [amanda] you guys ready</i>
<i>  to redistill these pears?</i>

29:11.050 --> 29:13.183
[huck] ready as we'll ever be,
I guess.

29:13.986 --> 29:15.252
[amanda] back at
the old still site

29:15.488 --> 29:16.320
it's a miracle.

29:16.689 --> 29:17.788
[amanda] it's a miracle.

29:17.790 --> 29:19.757
Well, today we made it
back to the still site

29:19.759 --> 29:21.024
with these two buckets
of infused liquor.

29:21.026 --> 29:22.559
<i>  It's a little bit dingy.</i>

29:22.561 --> 29:24.228
<i>  You know,</i>
<i>  it ain't real, real clear?</i>

29:24.230 --> 29:26.497
So that's the reason
we want to double-distill it.

29:26.499 --> 29:28.699
<i>  And hopefully,</i>
<i>  it's gonna be pure.</i>

29:28.701 --> 29:29.767
<i>  There ain't gonna be</i>
<i>  no sediment in it.</i>

29:29.769 --> 29:31.502
But right now,
it's just a gamble.

29:31.504 --> 29:34.071
So, just gonna have to see
how that turns out.

29:34.073 --> 29:36.940
You know what?
We're gonna let you
run that yourself.

29:36.942 --> 29:37.541
[amanda] really?

29:37.543 --> 29:39.243
Mmm-hmm. We are.

29:39.245 --> 29:41.645
We just want to sit back.
We want to monitor you.

29:41.647 --> 29:42.780
Watch you.

29:42.782 --> 29:43.614
[amanda] all right.
That's good practice.

29:43.616 --> 29:45.082
I think I can handle it.

29:45.084 --> 29:46.750
I think it'll be definitely
easier to fill
the still today.

29:46.752 --> 29:49.153
Lot less going in there.
[chuckles]

29:49.155 --> 29:51.054
<i>  the guys just told me</i>
<i>  that it's gonna be my job</i>
<i>  to run it</i>

29:51.056 --> 29:52.990
all by myself this time.

29:52.992 --> 29:55.626
So, I'm pretty honored,
because I want them

29:55.628 --> 29:59.263
to trust me and respect me,
and know
that I am also a moonshiner,

29:59.265 --> 30:01.131
<i>  and I can also</i>
<i>  pull my weight here.</i>

30:01.300 --> 30:02.933
Mmm. God!

30:02.935 --> 30:05.869
When we run this,
that'll tell the tale,
right there.

30:05.871 --> 30:07.171
All right.

30:07.173 --> 30:09.706
There's a ton of pressure.
And it's gonna be my chance

30:09.708 --> 30:11.375
to show them what I can do.

30:13.746 --> 30:14.778
[rogers] here you go, amanda.
Here you...

30:14.780 --> 30:16.947
-A little starting fluid here.
-[amanda] all right.

30:16.949 --> 30:19.149
Just be real careful,
I'll tell you. Don't spill it.

30:19.151 --> 30:20.818
Yes, sir.

30:20.820 --> 30:22.186
Step number one, be careful.

30:22.888 --> 30:24.021
[flicks lighter]

30:26.025 --> 30:28.592
<i>  so, cooking on an open fire</i>
<i>  through furnace heat?</i>

30:28.594 --> 30:30.127
<i>  Not a lot of people</i>
<i>  do that anymore.</i>

30:30.129 --> 30:32.896
And if I just get that flame
a little bit too hot,

30:32.898 --> 30:34.832
<i>  we could scorch</i>
<i>  the liquor, possibly, and...</i>

30:34.834 --> 30:37.467
<i>  And then the whole run</i>
<i> would be shot because of that.</i>

30:37.469 --> 30:40.838
So I gotta really make sure
that I pay attention
and watch those coals.

30:40.840 --> 30:42.840
<i> [mark] how's it coming</i>
<i>  over there?</i>

30:42.842 --> 30:43.807
-About ready.
-[mark] pretty close?

30:43.809 --> 30:46.510
Yeah. Steam's up
in this arm, here.

30:46.512 --> 30:48.879
<i> [huck] I'm a little bit</i>
<i>  nervous about rerunning it.</i>

30:48.881 --> 30:50.280
Might lose a little bit
of the flavor.

30:50.282 --> 30:51.481
Don't know yet.

30:51.483 --> 30:53.951
So what do you guys think
about the infusion, so far?

30:53.953 --> 30:55.419
It sure flavored it,
I'll tell you that.

30:55.421 --> 30:57.054
[amanda] yeah.

30:57.056 --> 30:58.789
I guess this right here
is gonna tell the tale though,
ain't it?

30:58.791 --> 30:59.723
It should.

30:59.725 --> 31:00.891
Normally, you'd probably
let it sit

31:00.893 --> 31:03.827
for six to eight weeks,
to get a smooth flavor.

31:03.829 --> 31:06.463
So, we're able
to squeeze it into 20 minutes.

31:06.465 --> 31:08.265
So it's pretty interesting
to see.

31:09.802 --> 31:12.035
Oops. She's running, guys.

31:17.042 --> 31:18.208
[huck] how does it smell?

31:18.944 --> 31:20.077
[amanda] it smells like pears.

31:20.079 --> 31:22.012
<i>  I feel like I'm getting</i>
<i> pretty nervous at this moment,</i>

31:22.014 --> 31:24.481
<i>  because I really want</i>
<i>  mark and huck to approve</i>

31:24.483 --> 31:25.916
<i>  of all the work</i>
<i>  that we've done.</i>

31:25.918 --> 31:27.484
So, now's the moment of truth.

31:30.923 --> 31:31.955
I can't believe this.

31:31.957 --> 31:33.857
[amanda] what do you think?

31:33.859 --> 31:35.492
That's just like
biting into a pear.

31:35.961 --> 31:36.960
[slurps]

31:37.096 --> 31:38.829
-that's some
good stuff, right there.
-It is.

31:38.831 --> 31:39.763
-That's good.
-[amanda] yeah?

31:39.765 --> 31:40.631
[rogers] yeah, move.

31:40.633 --> 31:44.701
Good pear taste.
Clear as a bell.
Happy.

31:44.703 --> 31:46.670
[rogers] y'all, I want
to get me a good
drink of this.

31:46.672 --> 31:48.472
-Clear as a bell, isn't it?
-Yeah.

31:48.474 --> 31:49.773
I'm really happy
with the final product.

31:49.775 --> 31:51.875
<i>  It tastes just like</i>
<i>  lora's pears.</i>

31:51.877 --> 31:53.844
<i>  So, we didn't overwhelm</i>
<i>  the base spirit,</i>

31:53.846 --> 31:56.413
and we were really able
to infuse it
with a ton of flavor.

31:56.415 --> 31:57.681
I'm getting warm.

31:57.683 --> 32:00.250
-All the way down
through my esophagus.
-[huck] mmm-hmm.

32:00.252 --> 32:01.952
